    "updated_at": "2016-02-02T16:32:38Z",
    "body": "Doesn't seem useless to me. The [reference](https://doc.rust-lang.org/reference.html#modules) gives this seemingly reasonable example:\n\n> The directories and files used for loading external file modules can be influenced with the path attribute.\n> \n> ``` rust\n> #[path = \"thread_files\"]\n> mod thread {\n>     // Load the `local_data` module from `thread_files/tls.rs`\n>     #[path = \"tls.rs\"]\n>     mod local_data;\n> }\n> ```\n\nNow suppose you're in a build script and want to include `src/tls.rs`. Is there a better way than\n\n``` rust\n// This module hides some optional stuff\n#[cfg(foo_bar)]\n#[path = \"\"]\nmod thread {\n    #[path = \"src/tls.rs\"]\n    mod local_data;\n}\n```\n",
